Ed Sealover


Reporter
Denver Business Journal







Related Content
            





                            Thought Leader: This tech CEO aims to draw students to STEM careers                        





                            Thought Leader: Goodwill's Stuart Davie gives a hand up                        



 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Platte 56, Littleton Riverfront Living                




See All Homes of the Day





 
























                Thought Leader Denny Marie Post answers quick questions            














 Enlarge





                Red Robin Gourmet Burgers CEO Denny Marie Post shows off her burger tattoo.            

                Kathleen Lavine / Denver Business Journal            








 



Denny Marie Post isn’t shocked that she wound up as a top executive for a popular chain of burger restaurants. But she never would have predicted she’d someday have a tattoo of a burger on her left shoulder too.
Yet, that is exactly what the CEO of Greenwood Village-based Red Robin Gourmet Burgers (Nasdaq: RRGB) got stenciled on her body at a leadership conference in March because managers reached a corporate guest-satisfaction goal in just six months that they’d been given 18 months to achieve. What began as a semi-joking suggestion that she’d put the symbol of the restaurant’s Billy Love Burger — a burger holding a heart — onto her skin became the “Get Denny Inked Challenge” that everyone in the company rallied around.













 Enlarge






                            Red Robin Gourmet Burgers CEO Denny Marie Post shows off her burger tattoo.                        
Kathleen Lavine / Denver Business Journal










 


She’s happy to lift a sleeve and show off her body art to anyone who’s heard the story because burgers, and Red Robin, are her world.
“I would have been shocked. I would have said ‘no way,’” she said of the suggestion that 22-year-old Denny would take such a step. “But we believe in acting with integrity. And the team did it’s part ... So, I have to as well.”

> Denny Marie Post answers the DBJ's rapid-fire Quick Queries in the video above.





Post started in advertising immediately out of journalism school but realized quickly that she was drawn more to the early development and innovation of products rather than just the promotion of the final product. So, she moved quickly into an executive role marketing a number of consumer-facing brands, from Burger King to Starbucks to a short stint at T-Mobile.
“I’m not analytical by nature, but I am strategic,” she said. “So, I see patrons and behaviors. And I think there is a lot of weight in observing human behavior.”
Though she’s only been with Red Robin now for six years, assuming the CEO position just in August 2016, Post can wax philosophically about why America has a love affair with a hunk of beef placed inside a bun.

People love being able to eat things that they can hold in their hand, which is a great social equalizer, she said. The burger is the easiest food, other than pizza and that’s why they are so popular. And for those wanting something more complex than a plain burger, it can be prepared a lot of different ways.




 


Red Robin has 24 basic burgers on its menu, plus limited-time specials, and Post estimates there have several hundred iterations of the burger since the restaurant’s founding in Washington state as a college hang-out in the 1960s.
But while it does most of its business in its gourmet line of burgers with specialty ingredients, she found during the chain’s efforts at offering a build-your-own burger menu that people were more conservative, preferring that the restaurant suggest unusual toppings.
Post has a bit of a wild side to her own palate. A burger topped with cheese curds is one of her favorites. She will only go so far, though; The foie gras burger she once tried still stands out as the worst idea for topping beef she’s ever eaten.
While the food must stand out, though, she believes Red Robin’s true place in the crowded burger restaurant-field will be defined by the interaction the staff and customers who take the time to sit down and enjoy a meal there in an increasingly fast-paced, grab-and-go world. That’s why it was customer-satisfaction scores, rather than profits or revenues, that was the benchmark used to determine whether she would tout the chain’s product on her body for the rest of her life.
And through that interaction, Post gets to observe more about the behaviors of customers that have fascinated her for so long.
“The real experience in full-service is in giving your experience over to somebody and giving your hour over to somebody,” Post said. “The good thing is it is not hard to make people happy in this industry.”
-------------------
Denny Marie Post
Title: CEO
Company: Red Robin Gourmet Burgers Inc.
Industry: Restaurant chain
Website: redrobin.com
Family: Married with a 23-year-old son
Favorite food-themed TV show: Chopped
Best Piece of Advice She’s Gotten: Don’t take it all too seriously

Ed Sealover covers government, health care, tourism, airlines, hospitality, restaurants and brewing for the Denver Business Journal. Phone: 303-803-9229.












